2025 Outlook:
Ohtani has scripted quite the résumé already over his seven MLB seasons: Rookie of the Year (2018), MVP honors (2021), first player in history to hit 30-plus homers while also striking out 200-plus batters (2022), back-to-back MVPs (2023-24) and, most recently, becoming the charter member of baseball's 50/50 club (2024). While further history book rewrites might seem logically unattainable for the now-30-year-old, it's still within the realm of possibility that he'll score a career-high total fantasy points in 2025 and/or set a personal best in Wins Above Replacement. As both a hitter and pitcher from 2021-23 -- his expected role once again in 2025 -- Ohtani <i>averaged</i> 214 fantasy points more than the league's next-best player annually, an advantage that can be readily exploited in ESPN's standard game with its daily transaction format. Ohtani's fantasy utility hinges heavily upon how your league handles him, but a universal, No. 1 overall case is a relatively easy one.

2025 Outlook:
It has been a whirlwind past two years for Skenes. His LSU Tigers won the 2023 College World Series behind his performance that earned him its Most Outstanding Player Award and he won the Dick Howser Trophy as college baseball's best player. Skenes was then selected No. 1 overall in that July's amateur draft, ultimately reaching the majors with the Pirates just 10 months later. He'd toss six hitless, 11-strikeout frames in only his second start, kicking off a historic campaign that ultimately earned him NL Rookie of the Year honors. Skenes' electric raw stuff (a 99-mph average fastball, slider and splinker) grades among the best in the majors already despite his youth, and he's already drawing favorite's odds for the 2025 Cy Young Award -- a testament to his overwhelming upside. If there's any reason to hesitate in building your fantasy team around him, it's that the Pirates have been cautious with his workload, coupled with the typical worries we have with young pitchers throwing large IP totals. But hey, isn't <i>every</i> pitcher an injury risk to some degree?

2025 Outlook:
Coming off a sizzling finish to 2023 where he scored the most SP fantasy points across his final eight starts, Skubal exploded with a 2024 for the ages, culminating in the AL Cy Young Award. He maintained his 2023 control gains (sixth-ranked 4.6 BB%), added another full tick to his average fastball velocity (third-ranked 96.8 mph), and delivered 20-plus fantasy points in a MLB-leading (tied with Zack Wheeler) 14 of his 31 starts. Best yet, Skubal maintained elite performance across the entire six-month calendar, scoring more points over the Tigers' final 81 regular-season games (279) than in their first 81 (274). It placed him at the forefront of the fantasy SP rankings, though as is true with almost any pitcher these days, he's not completely without risk, with 2017 Tommy John and August 2022 flexor tendon surgeries on his résumé. Hey, sometimes you have to close your eyes tight and roll the dice.

2025 Outlook:
In this era with a dwindling number of aces, Wheeler is a relative rarity. He and teammate Aaron Nola are the only pitchers to have made at least 30 starts and totaled 190-plus IP as many as four times over the past six seasons. Since the beginning of 2019, Wheeler's 2,413 fantasy points rank second, his 108 quality starts first, his 1,024 2/3 innings rank second, his 1,094 strikeouts third, his 3.14 ERA ninth and his 1.07 WHIP 10th. He also set personal bests as a 34-year-old in 2024 with his 2.57 ERA, 0.96 WHIP, .191 BAA and 26 quality starts, further signaling his skill set rating as one of the most stable at the position. Wheeler is a pitcher around whom you build your fantasy team.

2025 Outlook:
Amidst a bevy of talented, fastball-throwing frontline starters in Seattle, Gilbert has quietly emerged as a prospective ace. He has made noticeable gains in numerous statistical categories over the past two seasons, including WHIP, walk, strikeout, whiff and ground ball rates. Plus, he has cut roughly a half a run from his Statcast expected ERA in both of those campaigns. Gilbert's addition of a splitter in 2023 helped him become a more strikeout-oriented starter, and his move to a six-pitch repertoire with less fastball reliance in 2024 helped further diversify his skill set. While the Mariners offense probably hasn't improved to the point that he'll significantly boost last year's nine wins, Gilbert should again deliver excellent numbers otherwise. He's a solid fantasy building block.

Crochet didn't merely break out in his first season back in a pitching rotation since his Tennessee days -- his 2024 performance was historic. He became the first pitcher in the modern era to strike out at least 140 batters with 20 walks or fewer through his first 18 career starts, and seven consecutive strikeouts to begin his Sept. 1 start tied an AL record. Despite the White Sox's concerns about his workload, which increased over the course of the summer, Crochet maintained elite underlying skills, even if his 5.12 second-half ERA belied his talent. The Red Sox acquired him with the hopes he can further blossom into their staff ace. Considering his arrow pointed nowhere but up for the entirety of 2024, there's reason to believe he will. Crochet is a building-block pitcher for fantasy purposes.

The 2024 season was a disaster for Strider and his fantasy managers, as the No. 1 pitcher off most draft boards lasted just two starts before succumbing to season-ending elbow surgery -- though he had an internal brace procedure this time after having Tommy John surgery previously in 2019. Monitor his rehabilitation throughout spring training, as his prognosis could drive his draft value as high as a top-25 SP pick or more of a late-round flier.

2025 Outlook:
The centerpiece of the 2023-24 offseason's Juan Soto trade, King proved every bit as capable a starting pitcher across 30 starts for the Padres last season as he was over an eight-start stint for the Yankees to conclude 2023. In fact, King was one of only four pitchers to strike out at least 200 batters with a sub-3.00 ERA, joining both Cy Young Award winners (Chris Sale, Tarik Skubal) and Zack Wheeler. He only strengthened his underlying numbers over the season's second half, getting a whiff nearly one-third of the time hitters swung at any of his pitches. It sets up the right-hander well for a similarly productive 2025, albeit with some risk of ERA regression, as his Statcast xERA should be nearly three-quarters of a run higher. Still, that's a top-20 capable fantasy starter regardless of format.

2025 Outlook:
How you regard Burnes might come down to these conflicting thoughts: Is his precipitous, four-year pattern of declining strikeout rates worrisome, or does the Diamondbacks' six-year, $210 million commitment to the right-hander strengthen confidence in his skills? The answer might lie somewhere in between. Burnes and Logan Webb are the only pitchers with at least 95 starts, 60 quality starts and 590 IP over the past three seasons. That durailbity, combined with his repertoire tweaks -- he's increasingly going for minimizing hard contact rather than for swings and misses -- diminish the instinct to panic about possible skills erosion. Burnes might no longer be a Cy Young favorite, but he looks the part of dependable top-10 fantasy starting pitcher.

2025 Outlook:
Webb continues to be one of the game's most durable and reliable starters, despite fanning hitters at a below-average clip. Control and command remain Webb's bread and butter, along with an extreme groundball rate. His 613 innings since 2022 lead the majors, but his 529 strikeouts over that span rank 15th. Webb's ERA and WHIP are both top 10 among all starters with at least 500 innings over the past three seasons, but both are vulnerable to variance since Webb allows so many balls in play. Feeding into the concern is the fact that Webb's swinging-strike rate has declined each of the past three seasons. Accepting the low strikeout discount on Webb has been a fruitful endeavor, but it's reached the point where doing so invites more risk than may be evident by recent performance.

2025 Outlook:
Imanaga got off to a historic start with the Cubs last season, posting a 0.84 ERA across his first 53.2 innings, the lowest mark ever through a pitcher's first nine MLB starts. The lefty earned an All-Star selection in his first season stateside and finished third in the National League with 15 wins, while only George Kirby and Tarik Skubal ranked higher among qualified starters in terms of strikeout-to-walk ratio. Home runs were a problem on occasion -- Imanaga allowed multiple homers seven times -- and those concerns will follow him into 2025, as fantasy managers may hold their breath in tough matchups. The Cubs are working with him on that issue, and overall his stuff translated quite well as he made the jump from Nippon Professional Baseball at 30 years old. Expect some giveback, but Imanaga looks like a legitimate frontline starter, one probably best viewed as an SP2 for fantasy purposes.

The right-hander's velocity was down a tick in 2024 -- several ticks early on -- and the strikeouts dipped along with it. His surface numbers improved over the final two months, but the strikeouts never really rebounded, as he was below a 20 percent K rate in both August and September. Just one year ago, Gausman was treated as a borderline ace following a late-career breakout built on the strength of his trademark splitter. The market has perhaps overcorrected heading into 2025, though the massive decline in whiffs and tough division leave performance question marks and provide reason to invest elsewhere. Now 34, Gausman has two years remaining on his deal with the Blue Jays.

2025 Outlook:
Walker has been in the San Francisco system since being drafted out of Washington State in 2018. He made the slow climb up the organizational ladder as a reliever and finally made the big-league roster in 2023. This past season was the coming-out party, as Walker ended up as the primary closer for the Giants by the end of the season and was one of just two relievers to make at least 75 appearances and work at least 80 innings in 2024. While most pitchers have taken a step backward historically after such a season, Walker could pull a Brad Hand from 2016 and 2017 and repeat his success. Walker's delivery and stuff make it very tough for hitters to square him up, and with the closer job in hand, the right-hander is in great shape for 25-plus saves in 2025.

2025 Outlook:
No longer is Gallen being drafted as a borderline ace. He missed roughly a month of the 2024 season with a hamstring injury and his walk rate increased by more than three percentage points, which led to his WHIP jumping from 1.12 to 1.26. Gallen's knuckle curve remains an excellent put-away pitch, but his four-seam fastball and slider were entirely hittable last season. Perhaps Gallen has fallen further than he should. After all, the right-hander was a Cy Young finalist in the National League in 2023, he won 14 games in a down year and still does a lot well relative to most starting pitchers in MLB, including limiting homers. Take the name away and the underlying profile is not all that exciting, but Gallen's numbers over the last three years give him a case to be viewed as a third or fourth starter in fantasy entering 2025.

2025 Outlook:
While Ryan has established himself as a quality starting pitcher in Major League Baseball, injuries have delayed the full-on breakout. He went down in August with a Grade 2 teres major strain and never made it back onto the field last season, though the Twins said in November that Ryan was making good progress in his recovery. A groin injury derailed his 2023 season, but through it all the right-hander has made 79 starts over the past three seasons (31st in the majors in that span). His flyball tendencies make him susceptible to homers, but Ryan is stingy with walks and misses bats at an above-average clip with his five-pitch mix. More cautious players will want to wait and see how Ryan looks in the spring before jumping in with both feet while those with a higher level of risk tolerance should be eager to invest in the skills.
